========================================================================
  FINAL VERDICT:
  Is HORUS v3 a SINGLE-THRESHOLD or MULTI-ATTRACTOR system?
========================================================================

  MULTI-ATTRACTOR — TTI spread = 31.0× across regimes (min=0, max=31). Each regime has a distinct failure mechanism and onset point.

  Evidence summary:
    R1 (cancellation): linear residual accumulation
      → regime has its own accum-drift attractor
    R2 (exponent drift): geometric explosion with deterministic onset
      → saturation attractor with fixed depth
    R3 (boundary hammer): permanent oscillatory regime
      → boundary attractor with no clean TTI
    R4 (mixed injection): probabilistic interference onset
      → entropy-dissipation attractor

  Each regime converges to a DISTINCT failure attractor.
  These attractors are not unified by a single depth threshold.
  The C4 epoch_depth (16) was designed for R2-class failure only.
  R1 and R4 require different management (class-specific depth limits).
  R3 requires boundary-detection routing, not epoch management.

